			 ‚ÄúThe taxi dropped him off at the entrance of the Marriner S. Eccles building‚Äîa towering, rectilinear behemoth of Georgia marble. Neither quite elegant nor quite ugly, it cut a striking figure against the clear spring sky. In a city teeming with ornate symbols of power, it was maybe only natural that the real thing would be found in an otherwise unadorned structure. To its critics, the building exuded a neoclassical boredom as unimaginative as the four floors of functionaries who staffed it.‚Äù  
			
